06539nam a22007695i 9780822395362DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20122012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223953627 a10.1515/97808223953622doi  a(DE-B1597)552832  a(OCoLC)1156872262  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aPOL0280002bisacsh04a320.6223  aMB 24602rvk0(DE-625)rvk/122284:04aThe Argumentative Turn Revisited :bPublic Policy as Communicative Practice /ced. by Frank Fischer, Herbert Gottweis. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: The Argumentative Turn Revisited -- tPART I. Deliberative Policy Argumentation and Public Participation -- t1. Fostering Deliberation in the Forum and Beyond -- t2. Performing Place Governance Collaboratively -- tPART II. Discursive Politics and Argumentative Practices -- t3. Discursive Institutionalism -- t4. From Policy Frames to Discursive Politics -- tPART III. Policy Argumentation on the Internet and in Film -- t5. The Internet as a Space for Policy Deliberation -- t6. Multimedia and Urban Narratives in the Planning Process -- tPART IV. Policy Rhetoric, Argumentation, and Semiotics -- t7. Political Rhetoric and Stem Cell Policy in the United States -- t8. The Deep Semiotic Structure of Deservingness -- tPART V. Policy Argumentation in Critical Theory and Practice -- t9. The Argumentative Turn toward Deliberative Democracy -- t10. Poststructuralist Policy Analysis -- t11. Transformative Learning in Planning and Policy Deliberation -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRejecting the notion that policy analysis and planning are value-free technical endeavors, an argumentative approach takes into account the ways that policy is affected by other factors, including culture, discourse, and emotion. The contributors to this new collection consider how far argumentative policy analysis has come during the past two decades and how its theories continue to be refined through engagement with current thinking in social theory and with the real-life challenges facing contemporary policy makers.The approach speaks in particular to the limits of rationalistic, technoscientific policy making in the complex, unpredictable world of the early twenty-first century. These limits have been starkly illustrated by responses to events such as the environmental crisis, the near collapse of the world economy, and the disaster at the nuclear power plant in Fukushima, Japan. Addressing topics including deliberative democracy, collaborative planning, new media, rhetoric, policy frames, and transformative learning, the essays shed new light on the ways that policy is communicatively created, conveyed, understood, and implemented. Taken together, they show argumentative policy inquiry to be an urgently needed approach to policy analysis and planning.Contributors. Giovanni Attili, Hubertus Buchstein, Stephen Coleman, John S. Dryzek, Frank Fischer, Herbert Gottweis, Steven Griggs, Mary Hawkesworth, Patsy Healey, Carolyn M. Hendriks, David Howarth, Dirk Jörke, Alan Mandell, Leonie Sandercock, Vivien A. Schmidt, Sanford F. Schram  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDebates and debating. 0aPersuasion (Rhetoric)xElectronic books. 0aPersuasion (Rhetoric). 0aPolicy sciences. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aAttili, Giovanni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchstein, Hubertus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu